7.6 Performance of Body Fat Percentage Estimation
To evaluate the performance of body fat percentage estimation, R2 scores are computed with cross-validation lasso regression. We also evaluate the generalization performance by testing the regression model on cross-user scenario. The results are shown in Figure 16. Performance on Standalone Headsets. Using facial vibrations induced by human‚Äôs breathing, the cross-validation R2 scores are 0.5464 and 0.5245, 0.5112 for Meta Quest and HTC Vive Pro Eye. Utilizing heartbeat-induced vibrations, R2 scores can reach more than 0.6848 and 0.6595 for two commodity standalone AR/VR headsets. We also evaluate the performance of the body fat percentage estimation module on a group of samples from new users and the results are shown in Figure 16. From the evaluation results of Meta Quest and HTC Vive Pro Eye, the absolute error of body fat ratio estimation is less than 2.6% in most measurements. The results manifest that there exist correlations between fat percentage and facial vibrations features and our proposed method can perform well on estimating body fat percentage.
Performance On Low-end Headsets. For Google Cardboard, the cross-validation R2 scores are 0.5112 and 0.6536 for breathingand heartbeat-induced vibrations. The absolute error for crossuser testing is less than 5.0% in most cases, which illustrates the possibility of estimating body fat percentage using low-end AR/VR headsets.
